(lldb) why What is the root cause of this crash? Walk through the program state, identify the defect, and propose a fix in code. Cover both a minimal local fix and a more thorough root-cause fix if they differ.
                                                                                
    Program state when the crash is observed                                    
                                                                                
     1 main allocates three Node objects on the heap:                           
        • c → value 3, next = nullptr                                           
        • b → value 2, next = c                                                 
        • a → value 1, next = b                                                 
       The linked‑list structure in memory is therefore                         
                                                                                
        a (1) -> b (2) -> c (3) -> nullptr                                      
                                                                                
     2 main then invokes destroy_list(a).                                       
        • The function receives a pointer head that points to the first node    
          (a).                                                                  
        • The loop in destroy_list is written as                                
                                                                                
           for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; cur = cur->next) {            
               delete cur;                                                      
           }                                                                    
                                                                                
     3 What happens inside the loop                                             
        • Iteration 1 – cur points to a.                                        
          delete cur; frees the memory occupied by a.                           
          Immediately afterwards the loop’s “increment” step executes cur =     
          cur->next.                                                            
          At this point cur is a dangling pointer (it still holds the address   
          of the now‑freed a).                                                  
          The expression cur->next dereferences this dangling pointer,          
          invoking undefined behaviour – specifically a use‑after‑free.         
        • The same problem repeats for the remaining nodes (b, c) because       
          after each delete the loop still attempts to read cur->next.          
     4 The sanitizer/diagnostic prints “Use of deallocated memory”, which is    
       exactly the symptom of dereferencing a pointer after it has been freed.  
       The program crashes (or is flagged) while executing line 12 of           
       destroy_list.                                                            
                                                                                
    Root cause                                                                  
                                                                                
    The loop updates cur after the node has been deleted, causing it to read    
    from freed memory. This is a classic unsafe deletion pattern.               
                                                                                
    Minimal local fix                                                           
                                                                                
    Leave the ownership semantics intact but make the traversal safe by         
    storing the next pointer before the delete:                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         Node *cur = head;                                                      
         while (cur) {                                                          
             Node *next = cur->next;   // keep the next node alive              
             delete cur;               // free current node                     
             cur = next;               // move to the previously saved next     
     node                                                                       
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    (An equivalent rewrite using a simple while loop is also acceptable.)       
                                                                                
    More thorough root‑cause fix                                                
                                                                                
    While the above change eliminates the immediate crash, it still relies on   
    raw new/delete and manual pointer management, which is error‑prone. A more  
    robust approach is to:                                                      
                                                                                
     1 Encapsulate ownership using std::unique_ptr<Node> so that each node      
       automatically deletes its successor, eliminating manual delete calls.    
     2 Interface design – expose a container class (or a smart‑pointer list)    
       that manages the lifetime of nodes, ensuring destroy_list is never       
       called on partially‑freed structures.                                    
     3 Static analysis / sanitizers – enable compiler flags                     
       (-fsanitize=address,undefined) during development to catch such bugs     
       early.                                                                   
                                                                                
    Example using std::unique_ptr:                                              
                                                                                
                                                                                
     struct Node {                                                              
         int value;                                                             
         std::unique_ptr<Node> next;                                            
     };                                                                         
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(std::unique_ptr<Node> &head) {                    
         while (head) {                                                         
             head = std::move(head->next); // automatically deletes the         
     current node                                                               
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    In main:                                                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     auto c = std::make_unique<Node>(Node{3, nullptr});                         
     auto b = std::make_unique<Node>(Node{2, std::move(c)});                    
     auto a = std::make_unique<Node>(Node{1, std::move(b)});                    
     // a is automatically destroyed when it goes out of scope                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This eliminates manual delete entirely and makes double‑free /              
    use‑after‑free bugs impossible at the language level.                       
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Fix the unsafe deletion immediately                                         
                                                                                
    Replace the loop in destroy_list with a safe version that stores next       
    before deleting:                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     // file: program.cpp, line ~12                                             
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         Node *cur = head;                                                      
         while (cur != nullptr) {                                               
             Node *next = cur->next;   // save next pointer first               
             delete cur;                                                        
             cur = next;                                                        
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This change resolves the “use of deallocated memory” error by preventing    
    access to freed memory. If you want a longer‑term, safer solution, migrate  
    the linked‑list implementation to use std::unique_ptr as shown above.       
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
     • Apply the minimal fix shown above (store next before delete).            
     • For a more robust redesign, replace raw pointers with std::unique_ptr    
       and let ownership be automatic.                                          
                                                                                
